{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/crema-huh-what-is-it-good-for-f7bf4fa97897", "time": 1683013209.3834949, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/crema-huh-what-is-it-good-for-f7bf4fa97897/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Crema, huh, what is it good for?. Absolutely nothing | by Robert McKeon Aloe | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Crema, huh, what is it good for?", "description": "One of the classic attributes of espresso is crema. Many baristas look towards the crema quality as the key indicator of good shot quality. However, I do not. I\u2019m not a big fan of crema, and my\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://link.medium.com/TEzDqihTi9", "anchor_text": "stir a shot", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://mobile.twitter.com/espressofun?source=post_page---------------------------", "anchor_text": "Twitter", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://m.youtube.com/channel/UClgcmAtBMTmVVGANjtntXTw?source=post_page---------------------------", "anchor_text": "YouTube", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/robert-mckeon-aloe-01581595?source=post_page---------------------------", "anchor_text": "LinkedIn", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/deconstructed-coffee-split-roasting-grinding-and-layering-for-better-espresso-fd408c1ac535", "anchor_text": "Deconstructed Coffee: Split Roasting, Grinding, and Layering for Better Espresso", "paragraph_index": 15}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/pre-infusion-for-espresso-visual-cues-for-better-espresso-c23b2542152e", "anchor_text": "Pre-infusion for Espresso: Visual Cues for Better Espresso", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/p/8cf623ea27ef", "anchor_text": "To Stir or To Swirl: Better Espresso Experience", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/spicy-espresso-grind-hot-tamp-cold-36bb547211ef", "anchor_text": "Spicy Espresso: Grind Hot, Tamp Cold for Better Coffee", "paragraph_index": 18}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/coffee-solubility-in-espresso-an-initial-study-88f78a432e2c", "anchor_text": "Coffee Solubility in Espresso: An Initial Study", "paragraph_index": 19}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/staccato-tamping-improving-espresso-without-a-sifter-b22de5db28f6", "anchor_text": "Staccato Tamping: Improving Espresso without a Sifter", "paragraph_index": 20}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/@rmckeon/espresso-simulation-first-steps-in-computer-models-56e06fc9a13c", "anchor_text": "Espresso Simulation: First Steps in Computer Models", "paragraph_index": 21}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/overthinking-life/the-tale-of-a-stolen-espresso-machine-6cc24d2d21a3", "anchor_text": "The Tale of the Stolen Espresso Machine", "paragraph_index": 22}], "all_paragraphs": ["One of the classic attributes of espresso is crema. Many baristas look towards the crema quality as the key indicator of good shot quality. However, I do not.", "I\u2019m not a big fan of crema, and my journey through espresso has been one that reduces the amount of crema due to a shorter shot (lower output to input ratio), so it isn\u2019t something I paid particular attention to. A friend once asked me where\u2019s all the crema after watching me pull a shot without the typical crema. So I pushed more water through the puck into a different cup to prove it existed, but I wasn\u2019t going to drink it.", "However, being a person of data, I wanted to take a peak into crema and see if I could understand what makes it different than the rest of the coffee. The caveat is that I\u2019m mainly looking at crema from weight, solubles, and taste. I\u2019ll admit better analysis could be done, but considering I haven\u2019t seen any analysis on crema, I figured I would start here.", "I started with a superautomatic to test because it produced more crema than my shots on a manual. The crema is considered by some to be artificial because it is from a pressurized portafilter.", "The CO2 in the cup bubbles to the top pretty quickly.", "From here, I separated the crema.", "I used two spoons to scrap off the crema and compare.", "I used an Atago to measure TDS.", "I made sure to mix before measuring.", "I expected the crema to have a lower TDS than the rest of the shot, but it has almost the same. However, due to weight, it contributes to only 3% of all extracted coffee.", "I pulled a shot from la Pavoni into the first and second halves of the shot. The majority of the crema was in the second half which has much less of the extracted coffee.", "Looking only at the crema in the second half, it contributed only 2.8% of the total coffee solubles at 4.9% of the total volume. The crema has a higher TDS than the seconds.", "I presented two shots as a quick test to examine crema. I didn\u2019t do more tests to understand what particles are in the crema that might be different from the cup. The majority of the crema comes from the second half of the shot, and I already don\u2019t drink that part because I don\u2019t find a taste benefit. I don\u2019t like the second half on its own or mixed with the first half. I would rather water down the first half of a shot. So whatever potential taste benefit there might be to crema, I\u2019m not interested in pulling longer shots.", "However, I\u2019m not keen on removing crema. Some people remove the crema entirely, but I\u2019m firming in the \u201cstir a shot before I drink it\u201d camp.", "If you like, follow me on Twitter and YouTube where I post videos of espresso shots on different machines and espresso related stuff. You can also find me on LinkedIn.", "Deconstructed Coffee: Split Roasting, Grinding, and Layering for Better Espresso", "Pre-infusion for Espresso: Visual Cues for Better Espresso", "To Stir or To Swirl: Better Espresso Experience", "Spicy Espresso: Grind Hot, Tamp Cold for Better Coffee", "Coffee Solubility in Espresso: An Initial Study", "Staccato Tamping: Improving Espresso without a Sifter", "Espresso Simulation: First Steps in Computer Models", "The Tale of the Stolen Espresso Machine", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "I\u2019m in love with my Wife, my Kids, Espresso, Data Science, tomatoes, cooking, engineering, talking, family, Paris, and Italy, not necessarily in that order."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Ff7bf4fa97897&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fcrema-huh-what-is-it-good-for-f7bf4fa97897&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fcrema-huh-what-is-it-good-for-f7bf4fa97897&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fcrema-huh-what-is-it-good-for-f7bf4fa97897&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fcrema-huh-what-is-it-good-for-f7bf4f